            <pb n="5"/>
            <head type="work" rend="align(centre)">Diamonds &amp; Toads<lb/>&orn;</head>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="align(justify)"><c type="lettrine">T</c>HERE was a widow,<lb/>who had two
                daughters.<lb/>The eldest was very much like<lb/>her in the face and in
                humour.<lb/>They were both so disagreea&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ble and proud that
                there was<lb/>no living with them. The<lb/>youngest, who was the picture<lb/>of her
                father for sweetness of<lb/>
                <pb n="6"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">6</fw>
                <lb/> tamper, was the most beauti&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ful girl ever seen ; but
                she was<lb/>hated by her mother, who<lb/>made her eat in the kitchen,<lb/>and do all
                the work.</p>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>31D13</name>
                    <desc>adolescent, young woman, maiden</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">This poor child was forced<lb/>twice a day to
                draw water a&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>bove a mile from the house,<lb/>
                <pb n="7"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">7</fw>
                <lb/> and bring home a pitcher full<lb/>of it.</p>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>31D17</name>
                    <desc>old woman</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">One day as she was at the<lb/>fountain, there
                came to her a<lb/>poor woman, who begged of<lb/>her to let her
                drink.<lb/>&ldquo;With all my hearty, Goody,&rdquo;<lb/>said this pretty girl, and
                    rin&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>sing the pitcher, she took up<lb/>
                <pb n="8"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">8</fw>
                <lb/> some water from the clearest<lb/>part of the fountain, and gave<lb/>it to her,
                holding up the pit&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>cher that she might drink easy<lb/>When
                she had drank, she<lb/>said, &ldquo;You are so pretty, my<lb/>dear, and so mannerly,
                that<lb/>at every word you speak there<lb/>shall come out of your mouth<lb/>either a
                flower or a jewel.&rdquo;</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">When she came home, her<lb/>mother scolded her
                for stay&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ing so long at the fountain.<lb/>&ldquo; I beg
                your pardon, mamma,<lb/>(said the girl,) for not making<lb/>more haste; and there
                came<lb/>out of her mouth two dia&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>monds, two roses, and
                two<lb/>pearls. &ldquo;What is it I see<lb/>
                <pb n="9"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">9</fw>
                <lb/> there?&rdquo; said her mother.<lb/>&ldquo;How happens this child ?&rdquo;</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">The poor creature told her<lb/>all the
                circumstance, dropping<lb/>a great many diamonds.&mdash; &ldquo;In<lb/>good faith,
                (cried the mother)<lb/>I must send my child too.</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">Come, Fanny, look what<lb/>comes out of thy
                sister's<lb/>mouth, when she speaks!</p>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">Wouldst thou not be glad to<lb/>have such a
                gift? Thou hast<lb/>nothing to do but to go and<lb/>draw water out of the
                    foun&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>tain, and when a certain poor<lb/>woman asks you
                to let her<lb/>drink, give her civilly.&rdquo; &ldquo;It<lb/>would be a very pretty sight<lb/>
                <pb n="10"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">10</fw>
                <lb/> indeed, (said the ill&ndash;bred minx)<lb/>to see me draw water.&rdquo;</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">&ldquo; You shall go ,Hussey,<lb/>(said the
                mother,) and this<lb/>minute.&rdquo; Away she went,<lb/>grumbling all the way,
                taking<lb/>with her the best silver tan&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>kard.</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">She was no sooner at the<lb/>fountain, than she
                saw a lady<lb/>beautifully dressed who came<lb/>up to her and asked her to<lb/>let
                her drink. (This was the<lb/>very fairy who appeared to<lb/>her sister, but had
                altered<lb/>her dress.) &ldquo;Am I come hi&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ther, (said she
                proud saucy<lb/>slut,) to serve you with wa&ndash;
                <pb n="11" type="inWord"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">11</fw>
                <lb/> ter? I suppose the silver tan&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>kard was brought purely
                for<lb/>your ladyship. However you<lb/>may drink out of it, if you<lb/>have a
                fancy.&rdquo;</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">&ldquo; You are not over and a&ndash;<lb
                    type="inWord"/>bove mannerly, (answered the<lb/>fairy,) and since you are
                so<lb/>disobliging, at every word you<lb/>speak there shall come out of<lb/>your
                mouth, a snake or a<lb/>toad.&rdquo;</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">When her mother saw her<lb/>coming, she cried
                out, &ldquo;Well<lb/>daughter !&rdquo; &ldquo; Well mother!&rdquo;<lb/>replied the
                pert hussey, throw&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>ing out of her mouth two vi&ndash; <pb
                    type="inWord" n="12"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">12</fw>
                <lb/> pers and two toads. &ldquo;Oh !<lb/>mercy! (cried the mother,)<lb/>what is it
                I see ? Oh ! it is that<lb/>wretch, her sister, who has<lb/>occasioned all this ;
                but she<lb/>shall pay for it.&ldquo; And im&ndash;<lb type="inWord"/>mediately she
                ran to beat her.</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">The poor child ran away,<lb/>and went to hide
                in a forest.</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">The King's son, on his re&ndash;<lb
                    type="inWord"/>turn from hunting, met her<lb/>and seeing her a pretty
                girl,<lb/>asked her what she did there.<lb/>&ldquo;Alas ! Sir, my mamma
                has<lb/>turned me out of doors.&rdquo;</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">The prince seeing the pearls<lb/>and diamonds
                come out of her<lb/>
                <pb n="13"/>
                <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">13</fw>
                <lb/> mouth, bid her inform him<lb/>how that happened, which<lb/>she did ; and he
                fell in love<lb/>with her, considering that<lb/>such a gift was worth
                any<lb/>marriage portion, conducted<lb/>her to the palace, and married<lb/>her.</p>
            <lb/>
            <figure rend="align(centre)">
                <ic:iconClass>
                    <name>42D24</name>
                    <desc>civil marriage ceremony</desc>
                </ic:iconClass>
            </figure>

            <pb n="14"/>
            <fw type="pagenumber" rend="align(centre)">14</fw>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="first-indent(3) align(justify)">Her sister made herself so<lb/>much hated, that
                her mother<lb/>turned her off, and the wretch<lb/>having walked about a
                long<lb/>time without finding any body<lb/>to take her in, went to a cor&ndash;<lb
                    type="inWord"/>ner of a grove and died.</p>
            <lb/>
            <p rend="align(centre)">FINIS.</p>
